                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12529315" author="ssegu" created="Fri, 21 Sep 2007 06:42:55 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;When the statement is created if the resultSetType is not specified -  setFetchSize or setCursorName calls result in the ResultSet with TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY and CONCUR_UPDATABLE.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://manuals.sybase.com/onlinebooks/group-jc/jcg0600e/prjdbc/@Generic__BookTextView/3956&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://manuals.sybase.com/onlinebooks/group-jc/jcg0600e/prjdbc/@Generic__BookTextView/3956&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12529455" author="mikedd" created="Fri, 21 Sep 2007 16:07:05 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure this was the right fix for the problem. The change affects all databases not just Sybase. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It seems to me that the correct fix would be to delegate the resultSet type to the DBDictionary class, rather than changing the settings for all databases. &lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12529518" author="ssegu" created="Fri, 21 Sep 2007 19:04:33 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes my initial thought too was to override the prepareStatement(...) behavior in SybaseDictionary$SybaseConnection. But later noticed that our connection pool implementation is setting the ResultSetType for all DBs, so to keep it consistent I went the route of setting it at the DelegatingConnection level. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
